title: Grateful Dead Live at Winterland Arena on 1977-06-09
description:
Set 1

Mississippi Half Step, Jack Straw, They Love Each Other, Cassidy, Sunrise, Deal, Looks Like Rain, Loser, The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Samson & Delilah, Funiculi Funicula, Help On The Way-> Slipknot!-> Franklin's Tower, Estimated Prophet-> Saint Stephen-> Not Fade Away-> Drums-> Saint Stephen-> Terrapin Station-> Sugar Magnolia, E: U.S. Blues, E: One More Saturday Night*

*Second Encore

reviews.review_text: Good sound, great energy Good sounding AUD source, captures the energy of the band, and audience nicely.      Only through the first set so far but really liked the 1/2 Step and Jack Straw, Jerry is rippin.

Praise One of those recordings that reaLLy makes me wish that time travel was possible. Although, to have something so personal and at the same time imperfect (similar to 5/21/77 by Doug Lamarre) rounds out the entire experience. I consider myself an incredibly lucky person. Not only do we have unlimited resources for which we can discover any possible variation of music, we can actually discern preferences from them, too. After having my cherry popped by Cornell, I didn't think there was anything else for me out there in the wild, untamed abyss of Dead-dom.
That resolution was kind of ill-founded, because through much worship, and even more common sense practice, there is everything else to be discovered. Not just what the month of May has to say for itself. The middle eighties (down to the tail-end) boast some incredible music and tapes justly created. I'm rambling, but the idea is that having this tape is another crossed threshold. Into the sonic atmosphere of time travel.
